\part{Hydrologic processes}\label{p01:part01}

\chapter{Watershed and Hydrologic Processes}
\label{ch01:chap01}

\chaptermark{Watershed and Hydrologic Processes}

\contributor{Author Name
\affiliation{Affiliation text,
Scott Polar Research Institute,
Lensfield Road, Cambridge CB2 1ER}}

This chapter discusses hydrologic processes\index{analysis
methods related to design} and management of water resources
engineering structures. In this regard, the concept of a watershed
is introduced and its physical characteristics described,
qualitative and quantitative aspects of water balance examined, and
the notion of water resources protection and utilization discussed.
Furthermore, the five major hydrologic processes that control runoff
volume and flow rate, in particular peak discharge, are explored.

\section{Watershed and Water Balance}
\label{ch01:sec3.1}

This section introduces the concept of a watershed,\index{describes its
most important characteristics} and investigates components of water
balance. It also presents the basic analysis methods of water supply
and demand.

\begin{figure}
{\hspace*{-3pc}\fcolorbox{grey}{grey}{\vbox to 10pc{\hbox to 33pc{\ }}}}
\caption{A topographic map showing the process of delineating a watershed. The contour interval is 10 ft.}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Watershed concepts and characteristics}
\label{ch01:sec3.1.1}

A watershed (Figure) is the\index{land area from which
water tends} to flow downward due to gravity along a drainage network
to a single common point, called the outlet. The drainage network
can consist of natural streams, manmade channels, drainage ditches,
culverts, and storm sewers. Its boundary is defined by a ridge line
(which usually is not linear per se, but rather curvilinear), on
which any given point has a topographic elevation higher than the
two adjacent points along the straight line passing through the
three points and perpendicular to the ridge line (as shown by the
I-I$'$ elevation profile in Figure). Thus, water
inside the watershed cannot flow across its boundary due only to
gravity; likewise, water outside the boundary cannot flow into the
watershed only due to gravity. Thus, water
inside the watershed cannot flow across its boundary due only to
gravity; likewise, water outside the boundary cannot flow into the
watershed only due to gravity. Thus, water
inside the watershed cannot flow across its boundary due only to
gravity; likewise, water outside the boundary cannot flow into the
watershed only due to gravity.

