\begin{example}{\label{ch01:exa3.1}}
Figurea shows a\index{topographic map with a contour}
interval of 10 ft. Delineate the boundary of the watershed with its
outlet at W.

\solution The delineation can be implemented by following three\enlargethispage{13pt}
steps. First, identify the contours representing ridges and the
contours representing valleys. The V-shaped contours that point
toward lower elevation form a ridge, whereas the V-shaped contours
that point toward higher elevation form a valley. The identified
ridges and valleys are labeled in Figureb. Second,
start from outlet W to draw step-wise straight gradient lines along
the two ridges adjacent to the stream that drains the watershed, as
shown in Figureb. Note that any\index{line should always}
be perpendicular to its two intersect contours. Finally, make
necessary adjustments to ensure that any artificial high-elevation
obstructions (e.g., railroads and highways) or localized high spots
(i.e., closed contours) are considered as parts of the watershed
boundary. The finally delineated watershed boundary is shown in
Figurec.

\begin{nboxfig}
{\fcolorbox{grey}{grey}{\vbox to 10pc{\hbox to .5\textwidth{\ }}}}
{A topographic map showing the process of delineating a watershed. The contour interval is 10 ft.}
\end{nboxfig}
\end{example}

